        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Exaptation' = a trait that evolved for one purpose but ended up serving another (here, an area that evolved for visual tracking now handles reading). 'Co-opted' = taken over for a new use. 'Adaptation' = a feature that evolved BECAUSE of the function it now serves. The passage explicitly rules out adaptation for reading and proposes exaptation instead.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Match against the options", "text": "Walk each option. A says reading affected the structure of the brain in important ways — the opposite of the passage, which argues reading is too recent to have changed brain anatomy. B says the brain shows considerable individual variation in reading — the text says the reading spot is universal to within a few millimetres. C says reading developed due to recent brain anatomy changes — again the opposite; the brain hasn't changed, the brain was already capable. D says the brain had a potential for reading long before reading was invented — matches step 3 exactly.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is D. The whole 'reading paradox' is set up to support exactly this implication: the brain's reading capacity predates reading itself.", "tier": "essential"},
