# Q38 — Election Time, what is suggested about politicians? — ans A
add("var-2015-verb1-ELF-038", {
    "solution_path": "The 'Election Time' paragraph says 'in modern politics it simply does not do to tell the voters what is going to happen' and that parties 'pussyfoot around the subject' of tax rises and spending cuts. Politicians avoid admitting to cuts before elections — exactly what A claims.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "The prompt is 'What is suggested about politicians?' — so you need a claim about how politicians behave in this paragraph, not about education or the NHS specifically.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Locate the key sentences", "text": "Two sentences carry it. 'In modern politics it simply does not do to tell the voters what is going to happen.' And: 'Instead, the parties pussyfoot around the subject, telling us how they will protect vital services, avoid inflation, attack poverty and tax us fairly – all at the same time.'", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Restate in plain English", "text": "Everyone knows the deficit is huge and that taxes will go up or spending will be cut. But during an election politicians refuse to say so out loud. Instead they make vague positive promises (protect services, fight inflation, fight poverty, fair taxes) and tiptoe around the painful word: cuts.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Pussyfoot around' = to avoid speaking directly about a difficult subject; to tiptoe. 'Sacrosanct' = sacred, untouchable. 'Reined in' = brought under control. 'It does not do to tell' = it's not acceptable / politically wise to tell. The vocabulary all points to avoidance, not directness.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Match against the options", "text": "Walk each option. A says politicians rarely admit to reductions BEFORE elections — exact match: 'it does not do to tell the voters what is going to happen'. B says they spend less on education than on health — the text groups education and NHS as both 'sacrosanct', no ranking. C says they use artistic methods in propaganda — 'Monty Pythonesque' is an ironic adjective for the absurdity of the exchange, not literal artistic methods. D says they focus on cutbacks at rallies — the opposite; they AVOID the topic of cutbacks.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is A. The paragraph's whole point is that politicians dodge cut-talk during elections — and that's exactly what A says, calibrated to 'rarely admit'.", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "It's easy to read 'education and the National Health Service' as listing them in priority order, which sounds like a spending claim.", "why_wrong": "The passage groups them as BOTH 'sacrosanct' — equally untouchable. Step 5's text-check shows there's no ranking, just a pair. B invents a comparison the paragraph doesn't make."},
        {"letter": "C", "why_tempting": "'Monty Pythonesque' references comedy and theatre, so 'artistic methods' feels like a natural extension.", "why_wrong": "The Monty Python reference is IRONIC — it mocks the absurdity of election promises, not the use of art. Step 4's vocabulary work shows the register is satirical, not literal."},
        {"letter": "D", "why_tempting": "If you scan for 'spending cuts' in the paragraph, it's tempting to assume that's what politicians talk about at rallies.", "why_wrong": "The passage says politicians 'pussyfoot around' cuts — i.e. they DON'T concentrate on them. D inverts the verb. Step 3's paraphrase makes avoidance the headline."},
    ],
    "technique": "On 'what is suggested about X' items, find the verb-phrase the paragraph uses for X's behaviour ('pussyfoot around', 'invested with', 'tend to subvert'). The right option will paraphrase that verb. Trigger: prompt asks what is suggested or implied — read for hedged active verbs.",
    "pitfall": "Cultural references like 'Monty Pythonesque' are bait — they look like content but are tonal markers. Treat them as register cues (here: satire about absurd discourse), not as literal claims about content.",
})

# Q39 — Blogging, what are we told in this text? — ans D
add("var-2015-verb1-ELF-039", {
    "solution_path": "The 'Blogging' paragraph notes that 'blogging might trigger dopamine release, similar to stimulants like music, running and looking at art.' Running is physical exercise, so blogging is compared to physical exercise on the dopamine-release dimension — exactly what D says.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "The prompt is 'What are we told in this text?' — so you need a claim the paragraph actually makes, not a plausible inference about bloggers. Watch for options that invent details (medication, blog-writing volume).", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Locate the key sentences", "text": "The closing sentence is the headline: 'Also, blogging might trigger dopamine release, similar to stimulants like music, running and looking at art.' And the framing: 'something in the brain's limbic system is boosting their desire to communicate' (about drives generally).", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Restate in plain English", "text": "Flaherty's lab studies the brain's drive system — the same circuits that handle hunger and sex. Blogging seems to tap that drive system: it can be compulsive, and it may produce a dopamine hit, the same brain reward you get from running, music, or looking at art. Blogging works on the brain a bit like exercise does.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Hypergraphia' = an uncontrollable urge to write. 'Limbic system' = the brain region that handles drives — food, sex, motivation. 'Dopamine release' = the brain chemical hit associated with reward and pleasure. 'Stimulants like music, running and looking at art' — three everyday activities that share a dopamine signature; running is physical exercise.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Match against the options", "text": "Walk each option. A says there are similarities between problem-solving and writing style — never mentioned; the paragraph talks about drives, not styles. B says bloggers are addicted to dopamine MEDICATION — the text says blogging itself produces dopamine, not that bloggers take dopamine drugs; this fabricates a fact. C says people who talk a lot are often regular bloggers — the text says mania makes people talk a lot AND that drives are involved in blogging, but never claims an overlap between talkers and bloggers as a population. D says blogging in certain aspects can be compared to physical exercise — matches the closing sentence: running (= physical exercise) is one of the stimulants blogging resembles.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is D. The closing sentence puts blogging next to music, running, and art on the dopamine-release axis — running is physical exercise, so the comparison is explicit.", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "A", "why_tempting": "'Limbic system controls our drives, whether they are related to food, sex, appetite, or problem solving' mentions problem solving — easy to splice it together with 'writing style' for an answer.", "why_wrong": "Problem solving appears as ONE of many drives the limbic system handles; writing STYLE is never discussed. A fuses two unrelated phrases. Step 5's matching keeps the claims separate."},
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "If blogging 'triggers dopamine release', it sounds drug-like, so 'dopamine medication' feels like a small extension.", "why_wrong": "The text says blogging produces dopamine NATURALLY, like exercise — not that bloggers take dopamine drugs. B invents a medication that the paragraph never names. Step 4's vocabulary work distinguishes endogenous release from medication."},
        {"letter": "C", "why_tempting": "The paragraph mentions both 'mania makes people talk too much' and 'drives are involved in blogging', so connecting talkers and bloggers feels obvious.", "why_wrong": "Both behaviours are examples of the SAME underlying drive system, but the paragraph never claims that the SAME people both talk a lot and blog. C splices two illustrations into a correlation the text doesn't make."},
    ],
    "technique": "On 'what are we told' items, identify what the FINAL sentence of the paragraph asserts — that's usually the headline, and the right option paraphrases it directly. Distractors splice mid-paragraph details into invented connections.",
    "pitfall": "Multi-fact paragraphs (this one names mania, hypergraphia, limbic system, dopamine, and four stimulants) tempt you to combine separate facts into a single claim. Stay with what the text actually JOINS — here, blogging and running are joined by the dopamine label, nothing else.",
})

# Q40 — The 1960s — ans D
add("var-2015-verb1-ELF-040", {
    "solution_path": "The '1960s' paragraph notes that 'a famous writer like Gabriel García Márquez wrote One Hundred Years of Solitude with A Hard Day's Night on his turntable' and that 'the acid-tripping Steve Jobs eventually brought us the iMac' — famous, later-respectable figures behaved in distinctly counter-cultural ways. That matches D directly.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "The prompt is 'What is said about the 1960s?' — so you need a claim the paragraph makes about the decade, not a sweeping cultural ranking. Watch for options that exaggerate ('most creative', 'famous writers organising experiments').", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Locate the key sentences", "text": "Two examples carry the argument. 'A famous writer like Gabriel García Márquez wrote One Hundred Years of Solitude with A Hard Day's Night on his turntable.' And: 'the acid-tripping Steve Jobs eventually brought us the iMac.' Both lines pair a now-respectable figure with a flamboyantly unconventional 60s-era habit.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Restate in plain English", "text": "Looking back, the 60s feel strange. People we now think of as canonical — García Márquez the literary giant, Steve Jobs the tech founder, Doris Lessing the Nobel laureate — were doing genuinely weird, counter-cultural things at the time (writing literary fiction to Beatles records, taking acid, being grouped with avant-garde rockers like Captain Beefheart). The decade's establishment figures lived unconventional lives.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Cultural authority' = respect from the wider culture; the kind of status that gets you on a school syllabus. 'Acid-tripping' = taking LSD. 'Way out' = unconventional, far from the mainstream. 'Postmodern' = a style that broke with traditional realism in the late 20th century. 'Sleek and technocratic aura' = the polished, tech-friendly image these works now carry.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Match against the options", "text": "Walk each option. A says it was 'one of the most creative periods in modern history' — never claimed; the paragraph talks about a specific 60s-ness, not a creativity ranking. B says famous writers were organising writing experiments — there's no mention of organised experiments; García Márquez writing with the Beatles on isn't an experiment. C says philosophy was not considered important — the paragraph doesn't mention philosophy at all. D says well-established cultural celebrities led quite unconventional lives — matches step 3 line by line: García Márquez, Lessing, Jobs are all famous, all unconventionally behaved.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is D. The whole paragraph is built around a contrast: figures now seen as polished and respectable were, in the 60s, behaving in ways that look 'way out' today.", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "A", "why_tempting": "A paragraph about cultural celebrities in the 60s naturally invites a 'most creative decade' framing — it's a familiar pop-history claim.", "why_wrong": "The paragraph never ranks decades for creativity; it describes a TONE ('60s-ness') and contrasts later polish with earlier weirdness. A imports a generic cultural verdict the text doesn't make. Step 5's matching rules it out."},
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "García Márquez and Lessing are both writers, and writing experiments were a real 60s thing — easy to lump them together.", "why_wrong": "The paragraph mentions writers but never describes them as organising experiments; the actual claim is about their everyday cultural authority and unconventional habits. Step 2's locations have no organisation language."},
        {"letter": "C", "why_tempting": "If the 60s is being painted as flamboyant and counter-cultural, you might assume serious disciplines (philosophy) were sidelined.", "why_wrong": "Philosophy isn't mentioned anywhere in the paragraph. C answers a question the text doesn't ask. Step 4's vocabulary inventory shows the topic set: writers, musicians, tech founders — no philosophers."},
    ],
    "technique": "When a passage names two or three specific famous people doing eccentric things, the headline is almost always 'well-known figures were behaving unconventionally' — pick the option that combines fame with unconventional behaviour.",
    "pitfall": "Decade-summary questions tempt you with sweeping superlatives ('most creative', 'least philosophical'). The paragraph almost never makes superlative claims — it makes specific contrasts. Calibrate to the contrast, not to the cliché.",
})

