# Q31 — claiming incapacity benefits — ans C
add("var-2015-verb2-ELF-031", {
    "solution_path": "Gap 31 sits in 'more people were 31_____ incapacity benefits because of depression and other mental disorders than were on the dole.' The verb that fits the relationship 'receiving / applying for a state benefit' is 'claiming' — answer C.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "This is a gap-fill (cloze) question — pick the verb that best fits the blank. Cloze tests collocation: which verb is the natural partner of 'incapacity benefits'? Read the full sentence, then ask what action the verb needs to express.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Read the sentence around the gap", "text": "'more people were 31_____ incapacity benefits because of depression and other mental disorders than were on the dole.' Context: Layard is comparing two groups — people receiving incapacity benefits vs. people on the dole (unemployment benefit). The verb describes how someone GETS or APPLIES FOR a state benefit.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Identify the relationship", "text": "The verb needs to mean 'receiving / drawing / formally applying for' a benefit. In UK English, the standard collocation for benefits is 'to claim a benefit' — you claim Jobseeker's Allowance, you claim incapacity benefit. So the verb should be 'claiming'.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Promoting' = actively advertising or encouraging — you promote a product, not your own benefits claim. 'Hit by' = struck by an unwanted event; you can be 'hit by' a tax, but not by a benefit you receive. 'Claiming' = formally requesting and receiving a state payment ('to claim benefits' is the standard UK phrase). 'Deprived of' = having something taken away — the OPPOSITE of receiving.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Plug and test each option", "text": "A 'promoting incapacity benefits' — would mean advertising benefits, doesn't fit a population count. B 'hit by incapacity benefits' — benefits aren't a calamity people get hit by. C 'claiming incapacity benefits' — the standard idiom; the sentence reads cleanly. D 'deprived of incapacity benefits' — would mean denied them, but the comparison is with people 'on the dole', i.e. receiving a benefit, so the parallel demands 'receiving', not 'denied'.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is C. 'Claiming benefits' is the fixed UK collocation and the only option that fits the parallel with 'on the dole' (both groups are receiving a state payment).", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "A", "why_tempting": "It's easy to grab a generic positive-sounding verb if you don't know the UK idiom — 'promoting' sounds active and harmless.", "why_wrong": "Individuals don't 'promote' the benefits they personally receive — promotion is what an agency does for a product or policy. Step 4's collocation check rules this out."},
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "Depression and mental disorders are negative events, so 'hit by' feels emotionally matched.", "why_wrong": "The grammatical object is 'incapacity benefits', not the disorders — people are hit by the disorders, but they CLAIM the benefits. Step 2's bracketing pins what the verb attaches to."},
        {"letter": "D", "why_tempting": "If you read 'than were on the dole' as a contrast, 'deprived of' (i.e. without benefits) feels like the opposite group.", "why_wrong": "The dole IS a benefit, so being 'on the dole' parallels CLAIMING a benefit. Both groups are receiving state money — D inverts that. Step 5's parallel-check rules it out."},
    ],
    "technique": "On cloze verbs with state-benefit objects, default to the standard UK collocation: 'to claim a benefit'. Trigger: noun phrase like 'incapacity benefits', 'income support', 'pension' — the verb is almost always 'claim'.",
    "pitfall": "Cloze options often include a verb that LOOKS thematic (depression → 'hit by') and a verb that IS idiomatic ('claiming'). Pick by collocation, not by emotional fit — the right answer is the phrase that a native speaker would actually say.",
})

# Q32 — despite the economic gloom — ans D
add("var-2015-verb2-ELF-032", {
    "solution_path": "Gap 32 sits in 'But 32_____ the economic gloom, economists and policymakers have not lost their interest in happiness.' Even though the economy is grim, interest in happiness PERSISTS — the gap needs a contrast preposition, and only 'despite' fits. Answer D.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "This is a cloze question on a connective preposition. Decide the LOGICAL RELATION between the two clauses first — cause, contrast, time, manner — then pick the preposition that signals that relation.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Read the sentence around the gap", "text": "'But 32_____ the economic gloom, economists and policymakers have not lost their interest in happiness.' Two facts: (1) economic gloom — a depressing setting. (2) Interest in happiness is undimmed — a positive persistence. The two facts point in OPPOSITE directions, so the gap needs to signal contrast.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Identify the relationship", "text": "The relation is concession: GIVEN the economic gloom, you'd expect interest in happiness research to fade — but it hasn't. So the gap needs a word that means 'in spite of / regardless of'. That's the canonical 'despite' / 'in spite of' slot.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Owing to' = because of (causal); used when the second clause is the EFFECT of the first. 'Blaming' = attributing fault to; not a preposition for a setting. 'Prior to' = before (temporal). 'Despite' = in spite of; signals that the second clause happens DESPITE the first, the contrast preposition.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Plug and test each option", "text": "A 'owing to the economic gloom' — would say interest is caused BY the gloom, but the sentence starts with 'But' to signal the opposite. B 'blaming the economic gloom' — wrong part of speech and wrong logic; you don't blame a setting in this construction. C 'prior to the economic gloom' — would place the interest BEFORE the gloom, but the sentence is about the present, after the recession 'fixed' the unemployment problem. D 'despite the economic gloom' — signals that interest persists in spite of the bad setting; matches the 'But' and the persistence.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is D. 'Despite' is the only preposition that joins a negative setting (gloom) to a continuing positive activity (interest in happiness research).", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "A", "why_tempting": "Causal prepositions like 'owing to' are common in formal economics writing, so 'owing to the economic gloom' sounds register-correct.", "why_wrong": "The clause starts with 'But', which already signals contrast — adding a causal preposition would make the sentence contradict itself. Step 2's contrast-cue ('But') rules out causation."},
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "It's tempting if you read the gloom as the villain of the paragraph — and 'blaming' has a moralising tone.", "why_wrong": "'Blaming the economic gloom' is grammatically off — you'd need a participle phrase modifying a subject. The sentence needs a preposition introducing a setting, not a participle. Step 4's part-of-speech check rules it out."},
        {"letter": "C", "why_tempting": "'Prior to' is a clean formal preposition and a familiar option in cloze tests.", "why_wrong": "The paragraph above ('The subsequent recession fixed that') places the action AFTER the gloom set in. C would place the interest before the gloom — wrong temporal direction. Step 5's time check pins the order."},
    ],
    "technique": "On cloze connectives, the previous word in the sentence usually flags the relation — here 'But' announces a contrast, which fixes the answer at 'despite'. Trigger: cloze with a leading 'But' or 'However' before the gap — pick a contrast preposition.",
    "pitfall": "Causal ('owing to') and concessive ('despite') prepositions sound similar but mean OPPOSITE things. Always read the leading conjunction first — 'But' demands concession, 'so' or '...' allows cause.",
})

# Q33 — secure citizens' right to pursue happiness — ans B
add("var-2015-verb2-ELF-033", {
    "solution_path": "Gap 33 sits in 'the Declaration of Independence does not say that government should pursue the happiness of its citizens, only that it should 33_____ its citizens' unalienable right to pursue it for themselves.' The verb that fits a government's duty toward a right is 'secure' — protect and guarantee. Answer B.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "This is a cloze on a verb whose object is 'right' — what does a government DO to a right? Read the surrounding sentence and ask which verb names the action governments take to uphold rights.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Read the sentence around the gap", "text": "'…government should 33_____ its citizens' unalienable right to pursue it for themselves.' Context: the contrast is 'government should not PURSUE happiness directly, only X the right to pursue it'. The verb needs to mean 'protect, guarantee, make sure of'. This is in fact the actual Declaration of Independence phrasing — 'to secure these rights, Governments are instituted'.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Identify the relationship", "text": "Governments don't release rights, control rights, or recover rights — they SECURE them, in the sense of guaranteeing and protecting. The contrast the sentence sets up: government shouldn't deliver happiness, only secure the conditions in which citizens can pursue it themselves.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Release' = let go of, set free — used for prisoners or pressure, not rights. 'Secure' = make safe, guarantee — the standard verb for rights ('secure the right to vote', 'secure due process'). 'Control' = restrict or dominate — the OPPOSITE of guaranteeing a right. 'Recover' = get back something lost — implies the right was previously absent, which doesn't fit.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Plug and test each option", "text": "A 'release its citizens' right' — releasing a right doesn't make sense; rights aren't held captive. B 'secure its citizens' right' — exactly the Declaration's own verb; means guarantee/protect. C 'control its citizens' right' — would mean the government restricts the right, the opposite of upholding it. D 'recover its citizens' right' — implies the right was lost; the paragraph treats the right as ongoing, not something to recover.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is B. 'Secure rights' is the canonical idiom for what a government does to constitutional rights, and it fits the contrast the sentence builds (don't deliver happiness, only protect the right to pursue it).", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "A", "why_tempting": "'Release' has a freedom-related ring, and the Declaration is about freedom — easy to pair them.", "why_wrong": "'Release a right' is not idiomatic English; you release prisoners, pressure, or information, not rights. Step 4's vocabulary work pins the wrong direction."},
        {"letter": "C", "why_tempting": "Governments DO regulate things, so 'control the right' might feel like a plausible administrative verb.", "why_wrong": "Control means restrict — exactly what a government should NOT do to a right. The sentence contrasts pursuing happiness (too much) with the lighter duty of guaranteeing the right; control would overshoot in the other direction. Step 5's plug-test rules it out."},
        {"letter": "D", "why_tempting": "If you read 'unalienable right' as 'a right that should never be lost', 'recover' sounds like restoring it.", "why_wrong": "'Unalienable' means the right is ALWAYS there; nothing to recover. 'Recover' implies prior loss, which the paragraph doesn't claim. Step 3's relationship-check fixes this."},
    ],
    "technique": "On cloze verbs whose object is 'right', default to 'secure' — that's the standard legal/political collocation. Trigger: gap followed by 'right' or 'rights' — 'secure' is the canonical verb.",
    "pitfall": "Cloze prompts that paraphrase a famous text (here, the Declaration of Independence) hide the answer in plain sight — Jefferson's verb was 'secure'. When a passage echoes a famous source, the verb in the gap is often the source's verb.",
})

# Q34 — still fail to do so — ans D
add("var-2015-verb2-ELF-034", {
    "solution_path": "Gap 34 sits in 'sometimes people have the knowledge and the self-command to choose happiness, and they 34_____ fail to do so.' Despite having what they need, they STILL fail — the gap needs a concessive adverb, and 'still' is the only fit. Answer D.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "This is a cloze on a sentence adverb. Decide the LOGICAL RELATION between the two halves of the sentence — does the second half follow from the first, contradict it, qualify it? — then pick the adverb that signals that relation.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Read the sentence around the gap", "text": "'sometimes people have the knowledge and the self-command to choose happiness, and they 34_____ fail to do so.' First half: people HAVE what they need to choose happiness. Second half: they fail anyway. The relation is concession — the failure happens IN SPITE OF having the right tools.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Identify the relationship", "text": "The adverb needs to mean 'nevertheless, even so, regardless'. Out of the four options, 'still' is the natural concessive adverb in this position. The construction is canonical English: 'they have X, and they STILL fail' = 'they have X, yet they fail anyway'.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Consequently' = as a result; signals that the failure is CAUSED BY having the knowledge — wrong direction. 'Seldom' = rarely; would mean people rarely fail, but the paragraph is explaining the failure. 'Certainly' = without doubt; an emphasis adverb, not a relation. 'Still' = nevertheless, even so — the concessive adverb that fits 'X, and they STILL fail'.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Plug and test each option", "text": "A 'consequently fail' — would say the failure is CAUSED BY having the tools, which is the opposite of the intended logic. B 'seldom fail' — would say they rarely fail, but the next sentence ('Thus, in a recent study, about 70%...') explains a widespread failure pattern; seldom contradicts that. C 'certainly fail' — would mean inevitable failure, too absolute; the paragraph says 'sometimes'. D 'still fail' — signals concession: they have what they need, yet they fail anyway; matches the logic exactly.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is D. 'Still' is the concessive adverb that joins 'they have the knowledge' to 'they fail anyway' — and the rest of the paragraph (70% choose more sleep but stick with the demanding job) illustrates that gap.", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "A", "why_tempting": "'Consequently' is a formal connector that fits paragraphs about cause and effect, and the passage is about choice and outcome.", "why_wrong": "'Consequently' makes the failure a RESULT of having the tools — the opposite of the paragraph's logic, which is that people fail DESPITE having the tools. Step 5's plug-test flips the direction."},
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "If you read 'sometimes' in the first half, you might think the failure is rare — 'seldom' echoes that rarity.", "why_wrong": "'Sometimes' modifies 'people have the knowledge', not 'fail'. And the very next sentence (about 70% who would rather sleep but stick with the demanding job) describes a common failure pattern. Step 2's bracketing clears this up."},
        {"letter": "C", "why_tempting": "'Certainly fail' has a punchy, definite ring and matches the paragraph's confident voice.", "why_wrong": "'Certainly' would make failure inevitable, but the sentence opens with 'sometimes' — partial, not absolute. Step 4's vocabulary work makes the calibration explicit."},
    ],
    "technique": "On cloze adverbs in a 'they HAVE X, and they ___ Y' construction where Y contradicts X, the answer is the concessive adverb — 'still', 'nevertheless', 'yet'. Trigger: two clauses pointing in opposite directions joined by 'and'.",
    "pitfall": "Causal connectives ('consequently', 'thus') and concessive ones ('still', 'nevertheless') sound interchangeable in formal English but reverse the logic. Read the second clause first — if it CONTRADICTS the first, you need concession, not cause.",
})

# Q35 — still choose the higher-paying job — ans A
add("var-2015-verb2-ELF-035", {
    "solution_path": "Gap 35 sits in '17% of those who say they would be happier sleeping for longer and earning less also say they would still choose the 35_____ job.' If they would be happier earning LESS yet still choose a different job, that job must pay MORE — answer A, 'higher-paying'.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "This is a cloze on a noun-modifier; you need the adjective that fits the type of JOB being chosen. The trick: the surrounding sentence already tells you the contrast the choice represents.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Read the sentence around the gap", "text": "'17% of those who say they would be happier sleeping for longer and earning LESS also say they would still choose the 35_____ job.' Setup: a group says they'd be happier earning less, but they choose the OPPOSITE — a job that does NOT give them more sleep and less money. So the chosen job is one with MORE money and LESS sleep.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Identify the relationship", "text": "The whole paragraph builds the puzzle: people SAY money isn't everything, but when they CHOOSE, they pick money. So the chosen job must be the one with more money — the higher-paying option. The 'still' in 'still choose' marks the same concessive irony as Gap 34.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Higher-paying' = the job that pays more. 'Less demanding' = lighter workload — would match the wish for more sleep, not contradict it. 'Lower-paying' = the job that pays less — that's the one they SAY they'd prefer, not the one they choose. 'More demanding' = heavier workload — describes the SAME job as 'higher-paying' (work harder for more money) but pivots on a different axis; the paragraph's axis here is money, not workload.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Plug and test each option", "text": "A 'higher-paying job' — matches: people who say they'd be happier with less money STILL choose more money. B 'less demanding job' — would match the sleep wish, not contradict it; loses the irony the paragraph is building. C 'lower-paying job' — would be the consistent choice for someone who values happiness over money, not the surprising contradiction. D 'more demanding job' — describes the same kind of job as A on the workload axis, but the paragraph's spotlight is money/sleep, and 'demanding' adds work-effort information the sentence doesn't set up. The right axis is pay, so A wins over D.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is A. The whole point of the 17% statistic is the contradiction: people pick the higher-paying job even when they admit they'd be happier with less money and more sleep. 'Higher-paying' nails that ironic choice on the axis the paragraph cares about.", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "If they'd be happier with more sleep, 'less demanding' (= more time for sleep) sounds like the consistent choice.", "why_wrong": "The sentence is built around CONTRADICTION — the chosen job goes AGAINST the stated preference. 'Less demanding' would align with their stated preference, killing the irony. Step 3's relationship-check rules it out."},
        {"letter": "C", "why_tempting": "'Lower-paying' literally echoes 'earning less' from the first half of the sentence, so it feels lexically matched.", "why_wrong": "Lexical echo without logical inversion misses the point: the sentence pivots on 'still choose' — i.e. they choose the OPPOSITE of what they say. Step 5's plug-test makes the inversion explicit."},
        {"letter": "D", "why_tempting": "'More demanding' fits the picture of working harder for more money, and the paragraph criticises that lifestyle.", "why_wrong": "The two halves of the sentence are calibrated on the money axis ('earning less' vs. the gap), not the workload axis. D shifts axis and loses the contrast the sentence builds. Step 4's axis-pinning rules it out."},
    ],
    "technique": "On cloze contradictions ('they would be happier with X, but they STILL choose ___'), the gap fills with the OPPOSITE of X on the same axis. Trigger: 'still' or 'nevertheless' linking a stated preference to an actual choice — invert the preference.",
    "pitfall": "Statistics inside a cloze paragraph (17%, 70%) are tone markers, not content cues — they make the surprise feel evidential. The actual answer lives in the contrast verb ('still choose'), not in the percentages.",
})

