# Q37 — Orme's main result — ans C
add("var-2015-verb2-ELF-037", {
    "solution_path": "The review summarises Orme's argument: he 'challenges this assumption [that medieval childhood didn't exist] and convincingly argues that it is not merely flawed but untenable… childhood was recognised as a distinct state in both religious and secular law from about 1200.' Medieval childhood WAS separate from adulthood — exactly what C says.",
    "steps": [
        {"n": 1, "title": "Understand the question", "text": "The prompt asks for Orme's MAIN RESULT — the central historical finding the book argues for. So you need the option that captures his thesis, not a side detail about the 1960s historians.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 2, "title": "Locate the key sentences", "text": "The thesis sentence: 'In his informative and entertaining study, Nicholas Orme challenges this assumption and convincingly argues that it is not merely flawed but untenable.' And the evidence: 'childhood was recognised as a distinct state in both religious and secular law from about 1200. Before puberty, children were exempted from making confession, receiving Communion, paying tithes…'.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 3, "title": "Restate in plain English", "text": "Earlier historians claimed that medieval people didn't really think of childhood as a separate life stage — kids were treated as small adults. Orme proves that wrong. He shows that medieval law, church, and culture all explicitly recognised childhood as a distinct stage with its own rules (no confession, no marriage, no Communion before puberty). Medieval childhood WAS a thing — not a modern invention.", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 4, "title": "Vocabulary check", "text": "'Untenable' = a position that cannot be defended. 'Distinct state' = a recognised, separate category. 'Exempted from' = released from the obligation to. 'Annulled' = legally cancelled. The vocabulary all points to: childhood had its own legal and religious status, separate from adulthood.", "tier": "detail"},
        {"n": 5, "title": "Match against the options", "text": "Walk each option. A says medieval children were usually seen as smaller versions of adults — this is the 1960s historians' view that Orme DISPROVES, not his result. B says there is little legal differentiation between adults and children in the medieval period — the opposite of what Orme shows; he names confession, Communion, marriage as legal differences. C says childhood was regarded as separate from adulthood — exact match: 'childhood was recognised as a distinct state'. D says neither Church nor State believed children needed special protection — the review shows BOTH Church and State did treat them specially (Church exemptions, marriage law).", "tier": "essential"},
        {"n": 6, "title": "Conclusion", "text": "The answer is C. Orme's central historical finding is that medieval childhood was a recognised distinct status — and the review backs it up with religious and secular legal evidence.", "tier": "essential"},
    ],
    "distractors": [
        {"letter": "A", "why_tempting": "The 'small and inadequate adults' phrase appears prominently in the first paragraph, so it's easy to mistake for Orme's view.", "why_wrong": "That phrase belongs to the 1960s historians Orme is REFUTING — the next paragraph opens with 'Orme challenges this assumption'. Step 2 keeps you on the right author's claim."},
        {"letter": "B", "why_tempting": "Medieval law is often described as primitive or thin in pop history, so 'little legal differentiation' sounds plausible.", "why_wrong": "The review lists specific legal distinctions (confession, Communion, marriage age) drawn from the medieval canon — exactly the opposite of 'little differentiation'. Step 4's vocabulary work pins the legal richness."},
        {"letter": "D", "why_tempting": "If childhood wasn't recognised as separate (the rejected 1960s view), it would follow that no special protection existed.", "why_wrong": "That follows only from the WRONG starting point. Orme's actual position is that the Church and State both recognised and protected childhood — D adopts the loser's framing. Step 5's matching corrects the direction."},
    ],
    "technique": "When a review introduces an earlier view and then a 'but X challenges this' construction, the central result is the CHALLENGE — pick the option that opposes the earlier view, not the option that paraphrases it. Trigger: 'challenges this assumption', 'refutes', 'overturns' before the headline finding.",
    "pitfall": "Multi-paragraph reviews often state the WRONG view in the opening sentences (to set up the contradiction) and the RIGHT view later. Scan for the first 'but', 'however', or 'X argues' — that's where the actual thesis starts.",
})

